{{Infobox video game | title = Framed | italic title = | collapsible = | state = | image = FramedIcon-Pink.png | image_size = 256px | caption = App Icon | developer = Loveshack | publisher = | series = | platforms = [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]] | released = 12 November 2014 | genre = [[Puzzle]], [[Narrative]] | modes = [[Single-player]] | director = Joshua Boggs | designer = Joshua Boggs | artist = Oliver Browne | composer = Adrian Moore }}
'''''Framed''''' (Usually styled as ''FRAMED'') is a multi-award winning [[:wikt:noir|noir]]-[[puzzle game]] where the player re-arranges panels of an animated [[comic book]] to change the outcome of the story. Developed by the Australian studio Loveshack, Framed is an experience that sees the player changing the order of the narrative-based puzzles to a dance-meets-jazz score.<ref name="latimes"/>
A sequel, ''Framed 2'', was released 2017. ''Framed Collection'' is a compilation of Framed and Framed 2, available on [[Nintendo Switch]] and [[PC game|PC]].<ref>https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/framed-collection-review-worth-a-thousand-words/1900-6416912/</ref>
== Gameplay == Players take control of [[moral ambiguity|morally ambiguous]] characters as they slink their way across dark alleys and buildings in an effort to avoid the authorities and other obstacles. The goal of the game is to reorganize a series of [[comic panel]]s so that the protagonist is not caught by the police. In order to accomplish this feat, players must move frames around so that the [[sequence]] allows the main character to sneak past, avoid, or knock out their would-be captors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.148apps.com/reviews/framed-review/|title=FRAMED Review|work=148apps.com|accessdate=6 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idownloadblog.com/2014/11/26/framed-review/|title=FRAMED review: rewrite the plot to this espionage story|work=idownloadblog.com|accessdate=6 August 2015}}</ref>
