{{Expand Dutch|Hakken (dansstijl)|topic=culture|date=January 2015}} {{Infobox dance | name = Hakken | native_name = | native_name_lang = | etymology = | image = [[File:BranMoviC Hakken.gif|250px]] | alt = | caption = A gabber performing hakken | genre = [[Rave dance]] | signature = | instruments = | inventor = | year = 1990s | origin = [[Netherlands]] }}
'''Hakken''' (sometimes '''Hakkûh''') is a form of [[rave dance]] originating from the [[Netherlands|Dutch]] [[Hardcore techno|hardcore]] and [[gabber]] scene.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraaf.nl/filmenuitgaan/muziek/23411565/__10_jaar_Pandemonium___Hardcore_en_hakken___.html|title=10 jaar Pandemonium: 'Hardcore, hakken én gezelligheid'|work=[[De Telegraaf]]|publisher=[[Telegraaf Media Groep]]|date=5 December 2014|accessdate=12 December 2014|author=De Telegraaf|language=Dutch}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Mark van Bergen|title=Dutch Dance|date=September 2013|publisher=Xander Uitgevers B.V.|isbn=978-9-4016-0115-3|pages=272|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lVdjAQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&hl=es&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=12 December 2014|language=Dutch}}</ref> The dance is very similar to earlier European folk dance and is thought to be a sub form of [[zapateo]] with less airborne moves (unlike jumpstyle, for example, which features the "drunken sailor" style of jazz dance and high kicks). Music one is able to do the dance to is also called ''hakmuziek''. The name is derived from the Dutch verb ''hakken'' which generally means chopping, or hacking.
In [[Australia]], the dance is mainly referred to as gabber (noun) or gabbering (verb), named after the gabber subgenre of hardcore it is performed to. Despite the fact that it is called gabber, it is usually performed to music of the [[hardstyle]] genre by most people in Australia.{{cn|date=August 2017}}
The dance consists of small steps that quickly follow to each other to the rhythm of the [[bass drum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dj.dancecult.net/index.php/dancecult/article/view/523/495|title=How to Cure a Gabba|publisher=Dancecult|date=2014|accessdate=1 August 2015|first=Riccardo|last=Balli}}</ref> The lower body (down from the [[human pelvis|pelvis]]) is the most important part, though it is not unusual to move the arms and torso too. Because one is supposed to keep up to the beat of the song, the dance is usually done fairly quickly, since the [[Beats per minute|BPM]] of this music style can easily reach 190 BPM.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Frank van Gemert|author2=Dana Peterson|author3=Inger-Lise Lien|title=Street Gangs, Migration & Ethnicity|date=1 September 2008|publisher=Willan Publishing|isbn=978-1-84392-397-8|pages=304|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ru2ZzupdVXIC&printsec=frontcover&hl=es&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Ronald Hitzler|author2=Michaela Pfadenhauer|title=Techno-Soziologie: Erkundungen einer Jugendkultur|date=2001|publisher=Leske und Budrich|isbn=978-3-8100-2663-7|pages=400|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FofEGWFOedgC&printsec=frontcover&hl=es&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=12 December 2014|language=German}}</ref>
