'''Strength athletics in the United States''' refers to the various [[Strongman (strength athlete)|strongman]] events throughout United States and [[North America]] in the sport of [[strength athletics]] in association with the [[World's Strongest Man]] ("WSM") contest. America has both an amateur and a professional sanctioning body.
==Pro/Amateur organizations== American Strongman Corporation ("ASC") is the sole sanctioning body for all professional American strength athletes and organizes the annual America's Strongest Man contest,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://americanstrongman.com/|title=AMERICANSTRONGMAN.COM|website=americanstrongman.com}}</ref> as well as the NAS US Amateur National Championships, the winner of which receives their pro card to compete in professional contests.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=http://americanstrongman.com/?p=4074|title=AMERICANSTRONGMAN.COM|website=americanstrongman.com}}</ref> North American Strongman ("NASM") organizes the majority of the amateur contests in the United States, and holds pro qualifier events and national championship events throughout the year with men's, woman's, teen's and master's divisions as well as lightweight and heavyweight classes similar to ASC.
United States Strongman <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unitedstatesstrongman.com/|title=United States Strongman|website=United States Strongman}}</ref> is a relatively new organization.
==America's Strongest Man== {{Infobox sport tournament |year = 2015 |name = America's Strongest Man |image = |location = United States |establishment = 1997 |format = Multi-event competition |purse = |month_played = <!--Use if still played--> |current_champion = {{flagicon|USA}} [[Dimitar Savatinov (strongman)|Dimitar Savatinov]] }}
'''America's Strongest Man''' is an annual [[Strongman (strength athlete)|strongman]] competition held in the United States and featuring only [[United States|American]] athletes. The contest was established in 1997, with [[Mark Philippi]] winning the inaugural contest.
